    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/validation/nagaraja-cou1-stiffness-result",
      "type": "ValidationResult",
      "name": "Construct stiffness QoI comparison — primary validation result",
      "description": "Predicted construct stiffness (N/mm) from the FEA ensemble was compared against experimentally measured stiffness from N=11 ASTM F1717 compression-bending tests conducted across two independent laboratories (Lab A: n=6; Lab B: n=5). The FEA ensemble mean prediction of 312.4 N/mm fell within 4.7% of the pooled experimental mean of 327.6 N/mm. The validation metric E/uval was computed as 0.81, well below the 1.96 acceptance threshold. Uncertainty in the experimental measurements was characterized through inter-laboratory coefficient of variation (CV=3.2%) and intra-laboratory repeatability (CV=1.8%). Model input uncertainty was propagated via Latin Hypercube Sampling across titanium alloy elastic modulus (±5%), polyaxial screw head friction coefficient (±15%), and UHMWPE block modulus (±8%). The combined validation uncertainty budget was dominated by the friction coefficient term, contributing 61% of total uval. All three FEA codes (FDA in-house implicit solver, Ansys Mechanical 2022R2, DePuy Synthes proprietary solver) produced predictions within the acceptance band. The test protocol, specimen preparation, and data reduction procedures are documented in the companion test report TR-2023-0041. No anomalous specimens were excluded; all 11 constructs met dimensional acceptance criteria per ASTM F1717 Table 1.",
